[2] Georgia (Dade, Walker counties)
Date: Tue 2 Apr 2013
Source: The Red and Black [edited]
http://www.redandblack.com/ugalife/deadly-bat-disease-confirmed-in-georgia/article_d83f90d6-9b29-11e2-89dc-0019bb30f31a.html


About 4 weeks ago [early March 2013], Southeastern Cooperative Wildlife Disease Study (SCWD) researchers' fears were realized -- a fungal infection that kills hibernating bats has moved into Georgia from the Northeast.

"Once it was coming further south, we were hoping that because of the warm weather that we experience and the shorter hibernation periods, the bats would be able to make it better, and we had not been seeing the widespread mortality like they had in the Northeast," said Lisa Last, a postdoctoral research associate in the Department of Wildlife Disease Study. "Unfortunately, this year [2013], our fears have been confirmed; we have seen a lot of widespread mortality, as well."

Last works as SCWD's white nose syndrome surveillance coordinator at the University of Georgia [UGA], a program run through the College of Veterinary Medicine.

WNS is a disease caused by a fungus, _Geomyces destructans_, which lives in caves where bats hibernate. It can then grow on the hairless skin parts of bats, such as the ears and feet, but mostly the wings and muzzle. The fungal infection wakes bats up while they are hibernating, Last said.

Steven Castleberry, professor of wildlife ecology and management at UGA, said that waking a bat up in this manner can kill it. "The fungus apparently irritates them and causes them to wake up multiple times during the winter and they use all of their fat reserves, so it seems like they just starve to death," Castleberry said. "What you'll find are dead bats that are just completely emaciated and have no body fat."

Last said that the rate that bats are dying from WNS is significant. "In general, bats have been dying off at rates over 70 percent in affected caves, in a lot of places it is over 95 percent in an affected hibernaculum," Last said. A hibernaculum is the shelter for a hibernating animal -- in this case, the cave where bats hibernate.

Since early March [2013], Last and her colleagues received 4 bats to be tested for the disease from Dade and Walker counties, Last said.

Until that time, WNS was found in states surrounding Georgia, including just across the border in Tennessee's Chickamauga & Chattanooga National Military Park [CCNMP], Last said. According to a press release from The Georgia Department of Natural Resources, the US Fish & Wildlife Service and the National Park Service, infected bats were found in late February [2013] in Lookout Mountain Cave on the Georgia side of CCNMP. On 5 Mar 2013, the infection was also found in Sittons Cave in Cloudland Canyon State Park, a park located in Dade County.

WNS affects cave dwelling species of bats, including little brown bats and northern long-eared bats along the eastern seaboard, Castleberry said. Last said that all of the bats from Georgia which she received to diagnose were tri-colored bats, a small cave-dwelling species found throughout the Eastern United States.

Castleberry and Last both said that little brown bats used to be common, but their population could be in trouble. "In the Northeast, because they have been hit so hard, there are some reports out that they may go locally extinct in 15 to 20 years if the death rate continues," Last said.

The bats that are being affected seem to be from the same genus -- _Myotis_ -- except for the tri-colored bats, Last said.

"It was first found in 2006 in New York City, and the most common perception now is that it was brought in by cavers from Europe. It has spread down the Appalachian Chain pretty fast," said Jesse Thomas, a 2nd-year MS graduate student from McRae who wrote his senior thesis on WNS.

The fungus causes no known harm to humans, but they may be helping in its spreading. "With humans that's the big deal, trying to keep people from moving it cave to cave," Castleberry said.

[Byline: Jana French]

