[3] Commentary
Date: Wed, 3 Apr 2013
Source: Leslie Sturges <lsturges@verizon.net> [edited]


I thank ProMED-mail and its moderators for keeping us apprised of the devastation of WNS on North American insectivorous bats.

However, it is important to bear in mind that 6 years is a very short time in which to expect to see a resistant population, especially when WNS is caused by a cold-adapted, cave-adapted fungus, _Geomyces destructans_, which affects hibernating bats in caves. Hibernating, or torpid, bats are apparently in an immunosuppressed state in order to maintain prolonged torpor.

The rapid rise and spread of WNS and the low reproductive rate of the species affected do not suggest these species could develop any sort of resistant population in such a short timespan.

--
Leslie Sturges
President
The Save Lucy Campaign
http://www.saveLucytheBat.org

[The geographical distribution of WNS as of 29 Mar 2013 can be seen at http://whitenosesyndrome.org/resources/map.

A photo of a bat affected on nose and wings can be seen at http://media.treehugger.com/assets/images/2011/10/20100805-little-brown-bat-white-nose-syndrome.jpg.

Thanks to Leslie Sturges for sending her comment. I will have to disagree with her opinion, though. On one hand, the development of genetic resistance might not be necessarily slow. An increasing number of studies indicate that parasites represent powerful selective agents in natural populations. From Alitzer et al. 2003 (Trends Ecol Evol), "The observation that infectious diseases might be both mitigated by and rapidly change the genetic composition of host populations gives new significance to the role of host genetic diversity in species conservation." It should be taken into account that the survivors of an outbreak are very likely more resistant than those that died, so the population that would be exposed again to the pathogen has a different genetic composition in terms of _G. destructans_ resistance. On the other hand, even if 6 years is a very short time period to expect any development of intrinsic resistance, vertebrates have a wonderful defense system to provide them with protection in the short term: the adaptive (acquired) arm of the immune system. It is true that we still need to know more about how it works for this particular host-parasite system, but based on our current knowledge of epidemiology and immunology, we have sound reasons to keep on being hopeful! - Mod.PMB]
